text: This movie looks really cool, I can't wait to see it!  But you know, as a mexican there's something that bugs me a little bit. Whenever american movies or shows have a mexican or latino setting, they tend to rely a lot on jokes based on stereotypes, like people with bad english and mexican accent, or random spanish words in the middle of sentences.  And it's not because I find that offensive or anything (although I can see people getting offended by it), but because all of these jokes simply don't work in spanish.  When this movie gets dubbed in spanish, How this jokes are supposed to work when the punchline is someone saying something in spanish?  That's the reason I didn't like shows like Mucha Lucha or El Tigre, a Â lot of the humor doesn't make sense in spanish.  Anyway, it's awesome to see a movie inspired by Dia de los Muertos, and also with a lot of mexicans involved like Diego Luna and Kate del Castillo, as I said, I can't wait to see it.Â

text: In old times, Mexico used to be like this. I'm agree about that we, mexicans, are not in a desert with hats like that and guitars. But this movie is not about what Mexico represents it's about what we celebrate, called The Dead's Day. We are (maybe) the only country that celebrate its dead people.If you are from another country i can tell you that this celebration is awesome. We put an altar to the people that is not with us anymore. This is from November 1st to 3rd. We make fantastic food. It's a wonderful celebration. i think we made that day, because we can remember the people we love. Mexico is a cultural place that all this maybe will get lost. The new generations are coming with American stuff (no offense).Â

text: The plot of the movie is like the Corpse Bride.   Seeing from a more historical and national identity point, I think the plot is wrong about what are the traditions in Mexico. According to the clothing of the characters I see there is a strong Spanish influence, I think the time where the film is in Mexico the 17th or 19th century unfolds. Accordingly I must remind you that the tradition of the spirit world, deities and humans is governed from the center of everything (in fact mentions the teacher to explain what the book of life, which I think is the Popol Vuh of the Maya or Nahuatl tlalticpac universe) and for those who will see the film consider the traditions of Day of the Dead is not from Hispanic Mexico, is from prehispanic Mexico. I agree that Mexican and Spanish culture were mixed, but please this is far from reality.  I am Mexican and am studying history that is why I feel a little indignant, pardon for the sand in my vagina and my rusty english.

text: WHen i first heard of this film I was expecting something pretty terrible. Now after seeing this trailer it just looks okay. I will be completely honest that my biggest shame is that nearly every film centered on Latinos I have seen, American made and abroad, in recent years has been pretty bad. Like the comedies are often sappy and sentimental and are needlessly quirky and silly half the time. And what people make in America is often so filled with cultural references that all of the character feel like stereotypes and the entertaining kind like Tuco from The Good the Bad and The Ugly. And so often these movies (the American kind) force in a political agenda or a cultural message that it is impossible to enjoy what I am watching. And this coming from a guy who is otherwise a big supporter of these kind of things. What I really want is just a normal film starring Latinos that does not try to make a message and is entirely in English. Basically I just want the same approach white people use when making films for films starring other white people. That means never announcing they are white and just allow them to be characters going through a story that is never defined by their race.Â

text: in cultural anthropology I've learned that day of the dead used to be a long part of the 18 month calendar of the aztec, around the times of Â oct or november before columbus came. then it was only celebrated on all saints day nov. 1 and all souls day november 2. in my anthropology class our teacher said that they had to hide the traditional beliefs they had (aztec and maya) by celebrating them in sync with the catholic holidays.Â  so i wonder what this movie will be like. its a breath of fresh air to see that christian holidays are not the only ones recognized in mass media these days. it is a big deal i think, because kwanzaa was very short lived in the effort the mass media dealt in incorporating it, so hopefully this movie can lift the stigma. the inevitable however is that many in the U.S. will not understand how serious this holiday is and was to so many.Â

text: So basically, if no-one is around to remember you, or if your are the sort of bastard no-one WANTS to remember fondly, you go to this movie's version of Hell. Â My first thought is: doesn't that mean everyone is going to go to Hell eventually? I mean, for people who make it a point to honour your ancestors, how many generations back to you really remember? You might remember your parents, likely your grandparents, maybe a favorite aunt/uncle/cousin, but as the generations roll by everyone eventually gets forgotten. Even if there exists some sort of prayer that broadly covers ALL your ancestors, does getting filed under "et cetera" really count as being remembered?

text: Day of the Dead (Spanish: DÃ­a de Muertos) is a Mexican holiday observed throughout Mexico.The holiday focuses on gatherings of family and friends to pray for and remember friends and family members who have died. It is particularly celebrated in Mexico where the day is a bank holiday.Traditions connected with the holiday include building private altars called ofrendas, honoring the deceased using sugar skulls, marigolds, and the favorite foods and beverages of the departed, and visiting graves with these as gifts. They also leave possessions of the deceased.

text: Why is there sadistic Christian comments? Dia de Los Muertos is a Spanich holiday that's a merge of tradition between the Aztecs and the CATHOLIC church. It's a cute, family movie and coming from a Mexican family that actually celebrates and honors Day of the Dead, we're excited to see the movie and have parts of our culture visited and known.   This isn't blasphemy or cultural appropriation. This is more of cultural appreciation. To me, cultural appropriation is a white girl using sugar skull makeup as a Halloween costume. Which is the only problem I see with this movie, but at the same time, they're not insulting our culture.

text: I love this movie, it's a breath of fresh air to see original designs rather than the skin textures we see in dreamworks and Disney. BUT, there's two problems with this movie, one of them is the songs, the way they put modern pop songs with Mexican music is very distracting. If I want to make movie about "The day of the Dead" which is a real tradition in Mexico, I would put traditional Mexican songs that way the audience feels like they're part of this tradition, but hearing Creep by radio head and Just a friend by Biz Markie is very distracting and seems out of place in this movie. I wish it had more songs similar to the bull scene. My second problem is how the movie is a tad too predictable, honestly we all knew who Maria was gonna end up with and who was gonna win this bet, it's really obvious, it's also cliche, "The guy with the pure heart wins the girl of his dreams over the other guy with brawn."

There was a scraped note saying "Always sing from the heart" so he did. Over her time, Manolo was taught matador lessons from his dad Carlos.
